Date: 24 Apr 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Khaleej Times 22 Apr 2001 [edited
<http://www.khaleejtimes.com/middleeast.htm>

Kuwait on Saturday confirmed its first cases of foot & mouth disease
(FMD) in 3 years, becoming the third Gulf Arab state to recently
report instances of the disease, which is ravaging farms in Europe.
"We have found FMD cases in the Kabd area in the north of the country,
but we do not have the number of cases yet," said Wafaa Shehab, public
relations director at the Public Authority for Agriculture and Fish
(PAAF). "We have formed an emergency vaccination team and isolated the
infected cows and workers to prevent the spread of the disease," she
said. Farms in the Kabd area raise only cows.
There was a limited outbreak of FMD in Kuwait in 1998. Since January
[2001, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates have reported cases
of the highly contagious viral infection, which affects cloven-hoofed
animals but is harmless to humans. The al-Qabas newspaper said Kuwait
had discovered 250 cases of FMD in cattle farms in the Kabd area. A
farmer told the newspaper 65 of the 90 cows on his farm were infected.
Kabd farmers have asked the PAAF to vaccinate their livestock to
prevent the spread of the disease.
FMD has swept Britain and spread to parts of continental Europe.
Kuwait has already banned the import of livestock from all European
Union states following scares over mad cow disease.
